The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, August 12, 2004 				 RBI alert on fake foreign offers
 OUR CORRESPONDENT		 Reddy : Close watchNew Delhi, Aug. 11: The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) today cautioned investors on money-making opportunities offered by any offshore entities, including non-resident Indians.																								Public at large are cautioned not to fall prey to such fictitious offers or become a victim of the foul play of such miscreants, an RBI statement said.																								The statement said, Certain foreign entities/individuals are making offers of huge money through letters/e-mails for business development. Once, a response is received, a request is made for opening a foreign currency account or seeking details of bank accounts or an initial amount as deposit.																								The RBI also said remittance in any form towards participation in lottery schemes are prohibited under the Foreign Exchange Management Act (Fema). 																								These restrictions are also applicable to remittances for participation in lottery-like schemes functioning under names like money circulation, or remittances for the purpose of securing prize money/awards, RBI said.																								Besides remittances in foreign currency towards purchase of websites, any such scheme offering earnings in foreign currency on an incremental basis depending on the number of clients/customers added to the chain, thereby making the operation of such schemes akin to money circulation, is not allowed, said the statement. Gilts auction																								The Reserve Bank of India today received a lukewarm response for the auction of 91-day treasury bill for Rs 2,000 crore, including Rs 1,500 crore under the market stabilisation scheme.																								The auction for 91-day T-bill received 31 competitive bids totalling Rs 1,163 crore, RBI said in a release in Mumbai. The cut-off price was Rs 98.77.																								The central bank received two non-competitive bids totalling Rs 380 crore, which were accepted.
